<DOC><DOCNO> AP880419-0242 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-19-88 0230EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   04-19 0494</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0516</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The operating rate of American industry fellfor a second month in March despite a rebound at auto plants, thegovernment says.   The Federal Reserve said Monday that U.S. factories, mines andutilities operated at 82.3 percent of capacity last month, downfrom an operating rate of 82.4 percent in February.   U.S. factories had operated at 82.6 percent of capacity inJanuary, the highest level in more than eight years. In spite ofthe declines, analysts said the economy still shows plenty ofstrength.</TEXT><DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Chrysler Corp. plans to eliminate bonuses for topexecutives in years when it earns too little to share profits withworkers, the automaker's chief negotiator says.   Anthony St. John, a Chrysler vice president, revealed the planMonday after opening early national contract talks with the UnitedAuto Workers.   St. John said the No. 3 automaker agrees with the union's standthat it isn't fair for workers to receive no profit-sharing inyears when executives get fat bonuses or stock grants.</TEXT><DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Koppers Co. says it spent at least $3.5million in the first quarter resisting a hostile takeover bid byBeazer PLC, helping generate a quarterly loss of $8.5 million.   Meanwhile, the Beazer group on Monday extended its stalled, $1.7billion tender offer until midnight EDT Friday. Also, ShearsonLehman Hutton Inc. defended its controversial role in backing thetakeover.   The extension of the offer was expected since Friday, when afederal judge in Pittsburgh blocked the tender offer indefinitelyover apparent violations of securities laws.</TEXT><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Sears, Roebuck and Co., beset by sluggish retailsales and sharp declines in income from three of its four majordivisions, says its first-quarter profit fell more that 37 percentfrom the same period a year ago.   But sales were up 16 percent and industry analysts agreed Mondaywith Sears Chairman Edward A. Brennan that the rest of the yearshould be better.   The nation's largest retailer reported net income of $179.5million, or 47 cents a share, for the first three months of 1988,down from $287.9 million, or 75 cents a share, for the year-earlierperiod.</TEXT><DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Japan again has asked the United States to lifttrade sanctions imposed last year by President Reagan followingAmerican complaints over semiconductor sales.   Japan said Monday it had complied with requests to open itsmarkets to U.S.-made computer chips and that continued sanctionsonly would irritate Japanese manufacturers.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The British pound advanced again Monday, hitting a six-year highof more than $1.90 as an outbreak of fighting in the Persian Gulfheightened the importance of the North Sea oil fields.   Stocks weakened over fears of inflation and Gulf shootouts asthe Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slumped 5.81 points to2,008.12.   Gold prices rose and crude oil futures advanced.   Bond prices fell in the credit markets.</TEXT></DOC>